You've got an intermittent connection to the unit.  The plug from the
motor to the track unit is located on the back side of the door.  There
is also a switch that looks similar to your door plunger that turns the
motor off once it reaches the "back" position - the belt track gets to
that point and depresses the switch.  I would start with taking a look
at those connections and that switch, and also connections to/from the
motor which drives the track.  I believe the motor would be located
generally behind the right rear passenger armrest.  Hopefully digging
into there will yield an answer.

In general, these things are notorious in Fords of this general age.
I've had two of them, one a Cougar.  In my Tempo, it simply wore out,
and wouldn't retract all the way.  I ended up replacing the driver's
side unit with a take-out from a junkyard wreck in otherwise good shape.
Ford doesn't manufacture these any more.  If you did find a new one,
it would be pricey - about $750 or so, with the labor to replace it.  My
used one didn't last a year.  What I did (driver's side) was to slide
the belt along the track manually all the way to the "back" position,
and just unplugged the bugger.  It stays firmly in place.  I have to
sling it over myself when I get in the car, but it works, and passes
safety inspection.  I don't care about it; your passengers may not like
it, but it's the cheapest solution.

Best of luck...

